{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "Glitch",
  "description": "Glitch, decomposed into reusable field atoms: node.block_displace_field emits a per-block UV-offset field (RG) plus the raw per-block hash (R); node.scanline_jitter_field emits a per-row horizontal-offset field (R); node.mix(Add) sums the two offset fields; node.remap (Relative mode) warps the source by the summed offset; the RGB channel split is the inlined chromatic decomposition (node.radial_offset_field (Linear) → node.rgb_split, where the rgb_shift card binds straight to chromatic_displace.amount with the ×-1000 sensitivity carried as the binding's scale) rather than the fused node.chromatic_aberration; the per-block invert accent is built explicitly — block hash → node.exposure(amount) → node.smoothstep_texture(0.91, 0.92) → node.masked_mix over a node.invert; node.mix (Lerp, amount) crossfades the whole thing back over the source. Replaces the old fused node.glitch_displace (which bundled block displace + scanline jitter + invert mask in one pass) and the older node.glitch kernel. node.value fans the master `amount` to both fields, the invert gain, and the final crossfade; a second node.value fans `speed` to both fields so they animate in sync (as the legacy single speed did). Organized into three node groups named for what they do on screen: `Block Displacement` (the two offset fields summed and remapped onto the source so the image tears into jittering blocks and scanlines, emitting the block hash as a side output), `RGB Split` (radial direction field + chromatic_displace, the color-channel fringe), and `Invert Flash` (the block-hash-gated invert accent that flashes random blocks to negative). The groups flatten to a graph byte-identical in behavior to the ungrouped form; card bindings reach inner nodes by stable nodeId, so grouping never touches the performance surface. Documented visual deltas vs legacy: the scanline row index is taken from the original UV rather than the block-displaced UV (the fields are now independent); the chromatic split uses a fixed angle (legacy rotates it per time-step) and a fixed rgb_shift offset (legacy scaled it by amount, which the final crossfade now handles); the invert threshold is a narrow smoothstep rather than a hard step (slight AA at block edges). Time read from FrameTime.seconds — no generator_input needed.",
